        {
            "id": "589c962fa564408983b22",
            "questionText": "A solid cylindrical wheel with a radius of $!$R = 0.3\\,\\text{m}$!$ and a mass of $!$M = 15\\,\\text{kg}$!$ starts from rest and accelerates uniformly due to a constant torque applied to it. After $!$t = 5\\,\\text{s}$!$, the wheel reaches an angular velocity of $!$\\omega = 10\\,\\text{rad/s}$!$. How much work was done by the torque on the wheel during this 5-second interval?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "5ab66304ddf7443aaa312",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the formula for the moment of inertia $!$I$!$ of a solid cylinder. Please select the correct expression that relates $!$I$!$, the mass $!$M$!$, and the radius $!$R$!$ for a solid cylinder.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ce26676f-2505-496d-a13c-45eac6b1329c"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{2} M R^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = M R^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{3} M R$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "59a63c3d88d04a52b7b7c",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now that you have identified the moment of inertia formula, substitute the given values $!$M = 15\\,kg$!$ and $!$R = 0.3\\,m$!$ into the expression to calculate $!$I$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.675"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\u00b7m\u00b2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ce26676f-2505-496d-a13c-45eac6b1329c"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "ea2ab039c3b848dd83f52",
                    "stepText": "Moving on, we need the formula for rotational kinetic energy. Identify the correct expression that relates the rotational kinetic energy $!$K$!$, moment of inertia $!$I$!$, and angular velocity $!$\\omega$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "6352f0ee-0f0b-4829-ad63-9c74e3c1288d"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$K = \\frac{1}{2} I \\omega^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$K = I \\omega^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$K = \\frac{1}{2} M \\omega^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "9e48e28d6530430597309",
                    "stepText": "Excellent! Now, use the identified formula and the computed moment of inertia along with the given angular velocity $!$\\omega = 10\\,rad/s$!$ to calculate the rotational kinetic energy. This energy represents the change in rotational energy from rest.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "33.75"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "6352f0ee-0f0b-4829-ad63-9c74e3c1288d"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "b30f73dea70d4b02b9158",
                    "stepText": "Finally, considering that the wheel started from rest, the work done by the applied torque over the 5-second interval is equal to the increase in rotational kinetic energy. Which concept best relates work to the change in rotational kinetic energy?",
